        <h2 id="what-is">What is Moz Pro?</h2>
        <p>Moz Pro is an all-in-one SEO software platform founded by Rand Fishkin and Gillian Muessig in 2004 — originally launched as SEOmoz. The company serves <strong>40,000+ customers worldwide</strong>, is headquartered in Seattle, Washington, and is now part of the Ziff Davis family of brands.</p>

        <p>Moz is best known for pioneering the <strong>Domain Authority (DA)</strong> metric — still one of the most widely cited measures of website backlink strength in SEO.</p>

        <p>The product does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Link Explorer</strong> — backlink analysis backed by a 40T+ link index</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword Explorer</strong> — 1.25B+ keywords across 170 search engines</li>
          <li><strong>Site Crawl</strong> — technical SEO audits with weekly recrawls</li>
          <li><strong>Rank Tracker</strong> — daily SERP position monitoring</li>
          <li><strong>On-Page Grader</strong> — basic on-page scoring against a target keyword</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Moz Pro is <em>not</em>: a writing tool, a SERP-based content scorer (lags Surfer / Clearscope), or a full local SEO platform (MozLocal is a separate product).</p>

        <h2 id="features">Moz Pro features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Link Explorer — the strongest module</h3>
        <p>The 40T+ link index updates daily. Domain Authority (1–100) and Page Authority scores remain the most widely cited link-strength metrics outside Ahrefs Domain Rating. Useful features: Spam Score on every domain (great for outreach prep), Link Intersect for finding shared competitor links, and Top Pages by traffic.</p>

        <h3>2. Keyword Explorer</h3>
        <p>Access to 1.25B+ keywords across 170 search engines. Standard metrics: monthly volume, difficulty (0–100), organic CTR estimates, and Priority Score. Keyword Suggestions surfaces related terms, questions, and broad variants. Limitation: the keyword database is smaller than Semrush (25.7B) or Ahrefs (12.3B), which bites on long-tail and non-English research.</p>

        <h3>3. Site Crawl — technical SEO</h3>
        <p>Weekly recrawls with issue tracking. Catches crawl errors, redirect chains, duplicate content, and schema issues. Less granular than Ahrefs Site Audit or Semrush's 140+ checks, but adequate for in-house SEO teams.</p>

        <h3>4. Rank Tracker</h3>
        <p>Daily position updates with mobile + desktop split, SERP-feature tracking, and competitor comparison. Simpler than Ahrefs Rank Tracker but easier to set up for beginners.</p>

        <h3>5. On-Page Grader</h3>
        <p>The weakest module. Scores content against a target keyword on basic factors (title tag, H1, keyword density, meta description). Has nothing close to SERP-based scoring like Surfer or Clearscope. If you care about ranking content, plan to pair Moz with one of those tools.</p>

